SIMPLE: serenate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Serenate
<hw>Ser"e*nate</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[It. <ets>serenata</ets>. See
<er>Serenade</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A piece of vocal music,
especially one on an amoreus subject; a serenade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Or <qex>serenate</qex>, which the starved lover sings⟦br⟧
To his pround fair.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The name <xex>serenata</xex> was given by Italian
composers in the time of Handel, and by Handel himself, to a cantata of
a pastoreal of dramatic character, to a secular ode, etc.; also by
Mozart and others to an orchectral composition, in several movements,
midway between the suite of an earlier period and the modern
symphony.</note> <rj><au>Grove.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Serene</ent>⟦br⟧
